{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":1145,"record_hash":"sha256:44732a70370839db1ab721121c4aa021d3444c4a90baaf6032f54a263878ed78","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:21:43.990Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n AWS path if needed:\n \n-- Prefer EC2 + EBS for the live cache. EBS is durable block storage that can be\n-  mounted and used like normal disk\n+- If the team already has AWS infrastructure and wants to avoid another\n+  platform, use **one EC2 instance + one EBS data volume** for v1. This is the\n+  AWS equivalent of the Fly Machine + Volume shape: one app, one block device,\n+  one writer.\n+- Run the Agent Trail app in Docker or systemd on the instance. Install `git` in\n+  the image or host package set. Mount the EBS volume at `/data` or\n+  `/var/lib/agent-trail`.\n+- Use Systems Manager Session Manager for shell access rather than opening SSH\n+  broadly ([Session Manager](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/session-manager.html)).\n+- Use Amazon Data Lifecycle Manager for EBS snapshot retention\n+  ([DLM snapshots](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n+- EBS is durable block storage that can be mounted and used like normal disk\n   ([EBS volumes](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/ebs/latest/userguide/ebs-volumes.html)).\n-- ECS/Fargate with ephemeral storage plus object-storage result cache is a valid\n-  measurement spike, not the default product architecture\n+- Lightsail + attached block storage is the simplest AWS-console path if the\n+  organization allows Lightsail. It is fine for prototype/small v1, but EC2 +\n+  EBS is the cleaner choice if the app needs normal [REDACTED:entropy]\n+  integration ([Lightsail disks](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n+- ECS/Fargate with ephemeral storage plus object-storage result cache is a valid\n+  measurement spike, not the default product architecture\n   ([Fargate task storage](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n+- ECS/Fargate EBS is not the easy button for this. ECS can attach one EBS volume\n+  per task, but service-managed EBS volumes are deleted when the task terminates;\n+  the official storage table describes EBS as ephemeral when attached to a task\n+  maintained by a service\n+  ([ECS EBS volumes](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html),\n+  [ECS storage options](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n+  Preserving EBS data across Fargate task replacement needs extra lifecycle\n+  machinery around snapshots/replacement tasks, which is too much for v1\n+  ([AWS Fargate + EBS lifecycle](https://aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy])).\n - Lambda + EFS and ECS + EFS can work technically, but they introduce VPC, mount\n   targets, IAM, throughput modes, network filesystem semantics, and more\n   operational surface. Use them only if the product is already committed to AWS\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:21:43.990Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}